    <h1><strong>MESMIS</strong> PROJECT</h1>
    <div class="separator"></div>
    <div class="section">
      <a name="1.1"></a>
      <h2>WHAT IS THE MESMIS PROJECT?</h2>
      <p>The MESMIS Project is an impelled and directed effort by professionals and researchers from different areas who are interested in the development and spread of the tools for the evaluation of the sustainability of natural resources management systems. The project objectives are focused in the development of the Framework for the Evaluation of Natural Resource Management Systems Incorporating Sustainability Indicators (MESMIS) as in its application in case studies across the rural sector, mainly in farmers contexts of Latin America. Furthermore, it is looking to train individuals and organizations interested in evaluating the sustainability and formation of human resources through graduate an undergraduate university programs.</p>
      <p>To break with the common problem that the theoreticaldevelopments are applied just a few times inthe concrete society problems resolution (in our society concrete problems resolution) the project was designed to cover four main fields: research-train-apply-document. This, at the same time, gave place to four notable strongly integrate action areas: 
</p>
      <h3>1. Research in emergent topics of sustainability</h3>
      <p>where it is sought to contribute elements for the concepts development and tools for the evaluation, as well as a critical analysis of the opportunities and challenges that still exist for the operation of the sustainability concept. The different thematic areas where it has been deepened are:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>The trends analysis in the sustainability evaluation</li>
        <li>The characterization of managing systems</li>
        <li>Sustainability Indicators</li>
        <li>Integration of Sustainability Indicators</li>
        <li>Multi-scale Analysis</li>
        <li>Dynamic Systems</li>
        <li>Decision-making</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>2. Application and systemization of case studies</h3>
      <p>The systemizing experiences in theapplication of the MESMIS framework has been one of the principal concerns of the project. The case studies document how themethodology has been applied in diverse systems, ecological contexts and socioeconomic situations, from the southern tip of South America to the Iberian Peninsula. Among these experiences there are case studies of small-scale wine production systems in Argentina and Portugal, diversified multi-level ecological production in the Andes and communal management of forests and jungles, silvo-pasture agroforestry systems and small-scale ranching in Mexico.</p>
      <h3>3. Human Resources Formation</h3>
      <p>This area has been a pillar of the MESMIS project and has helped to train an ample group of persons with a new approach to themulti-dimensionality of natural resources management and its associated ecosystems. It has tried to cover diverse educational spheres:university undergraduate and graduate programs in Mexico and Spain, international courses and training workshops forcivil servants, technicians and rural promoters. </p>
      <h3>4. Generation of reference materialsfor public information</h3>
      <p>The MESMIS project is also creates reference materials to provide theoretic and methodological bases for understanding the concept and evaluatingsustainability in order to promote its discussion and use. This materials include publications in the form of refereed articles, books, reports and working documents, as well as the database SUSTENTA, which includes a group of selected references on sustainability and its evaluation. </p>
      <p>For detailed information about the MESMIS project, research areas and systematized case studies, see Astier et al. 2008  <a 
href="http://www.ciga.unam.mx/ciga/images/stories/publicaciones/sustentabilidad/GIRA_CS3_final.pdf" 
target="blank">Astier et al. 2008</a></p>
