      <a name="1.4"></a>
      <h2>THE TEAM</h2>
      <p align="center"><?php echo image_tag('static/about_us_team.jpg', 'alt="Equipo de trabajo"') ?></p>
      <h3>Dr. Marta Astier</h3>
      <p>Marta is a researcher at the Centro de investigaciones en Geografía Ambiental (Environmental Geography Research Center, CIGA-UNAM). She has worked in and published articles on ecological agriculture, particularly,soilquality and maize production systems. As part of the research team, her topics are sustainability of farmer productive systems, agronomic indicators and synergic and “trade-off” relations among indicators, and systemization of case studies that use the MESMIS framework. </p>
      <h3>Dr. Omar Masera</h3>
      <p>Omar is a full researcher at the Centro de Investigaciones en Ecosistemas(Ecosystems Research Center, CIECO-UNAM) and advisor of GIRA A.C.. His work lines are energy and natural resources, global climate change, andsustainability. His efforts within this last topic have been focused on developing the theoretical bases of the concept and its application in the management systems of natural resources, giving emphasis in integrating the social and natural dimensions. </p>
      <h3>Dr. Luis García Barrios</h3>
      <p>Luis is a researcher at the Colegio de la Frontera Sur (ECOSUR), San Cristobal de las Casas campus (Chiapas). His research line is focused on developing and analyzing the theoretical bases of complex systems, their proprieties or attributes and their application in the evaluation of alternative production systems, as well as the design of interactive simulation models for both teaching related concepts to dynamic systems andapplying them to practical problems in natural resources management. </p>
      <h3>Dr. Carlos González Esquivel</h3>
      <p>Carlos is a researcher in the Centro de Investigaciones en Geografía Ambiental (Environmental Geography Research Center, CIGA-UNAM). He has developed a research line focusedon the sustainability of livestock production systems. His work has been centered in the generation of theoretical and practice tools in the sphere of livestock indicators and their application in diverse case studies of the Valle de Toluca, Mexico.</p>
	    <h3>Dr. Santiago López-Ridaura</h3>
      <p>Santiago is a researcher in the Institut National de la Recherche Agronomique (National Institute for Agricultural Research) in Montpellier, France. He also collaborates as an advisorfor GIRA A.C. His work has focused on the evaluation and design of innovative agricultural systems integrating crop association, as well as on the development and implementation of multi-scale analysis at the regional scale.</p>
      <h3>MSc. Tamara Ortiz</h3>
      <p>Tamara works in the Outreach unit of the CIECO-UNAM, where she promotes articulation of research with society’s concrete problems. She has participated in the MESMIS project for several years and has been a key member in the promotion and organization of courses and workshops about the framework. Her interest topics are the characterization the management systems and studies of the participatory processes in sustainability evaluations.
</p>
      <h3>Anthropologist Jessica Fong</h3>
      <p>She has participated in researchin environmental culture and policyon the Mexico-United States border as well as in the Patzcuaro lake area. Her interests are the social and cultural development dimensions. She is now assisting the MESMIS project.</p>
      <h3>MSc. Yankuic Galván-Miyoshi</h3>
      <p>He has collaborated in the Project since more than five years ago in different areas. He is interested in the sustainability, natural resources management and the implementation of land use fields. In the MESMIS project, he has specialized in multi-criteria methods for the integration of the sustainability indicators. </p>
